<ContentPage
  title="Cookie Statement — Analytics Cookies Only | LazyTools"
  description="LazyTools uses one set of cookies: Google Analytics, to measure page visits. We set no advertising cookies and do no cross-site ad-targeting. Some tools also save your preferences in your browser's own local storage, which never leaves your device."
  heading="Cookie Statement"
  updated="July 12, 2026"
>
  <p>
    <strong>The only cookies LazyTools sets are analytics cookies</strong> — from Google Analytics, which we use to
    measure how many people visit each tool. We set <strong>no advertising or marketing cookies</strong> and do no
    cross-site ad-targeting. You can <a href="/privacy/#optout">opt out of analytics</a> at any time, and the tools
    work exactly the same either way.
  </p>

  <h2>What we use</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Google Analytics cookies.</strong> Google's analytics tag sets first-party cookies (for example <code>_ga</code> and <code>_ga_&lt;id&gt;</code>) to count visits and distinguish returning visitors. They record which pages are viewed — never the content you enter into a tool. See the <a href="/privacy/">privacy policy</a> for detail and <a href="/privacy/#optout">how to opt out</a>.</li>
    <li><strong>Local storage, kept locally.</strong> Some tools remember your preferences or saved data — Pomodoro settings, Kanban boards, a saved unit, whether you've rated a tool — using your browser's own local storage. This is <em>not</em> a cookie: it stays on your device, is never transmitted to us, and you can clear it any time via your browser settings.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What we don't use</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>No advertising or marketing cookies.</li>
    <li>No cross-site ad-targeting, and we do not sell or share your data for advertising.</li>
    <li>No cookies tied to your tool content — the files and values you process never reach a server in the first place.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How to opt out</h2>
  <p>
    Install Google's <a href="https://tools.google.com/dlpage/gaoptout" rel="noopener">Analytics Opt-out Add-on</a>,
    use your browser's tracking protection or a content blocker, or block analytics cookies in your browser
    settings. Clearing cookies removes the identifiers already stored. Full details are in the
    <a href="/privacy/#optout">privacy policy</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>A note on server logs</h2>
  <p>
    Loading any website means your browser makes a request to a server, and — like every host — ours keeps
    standard access logs (see the <a href="/privacy/">privacy policy</a>). That's ordinary web infrastructure,
    not a cookie.
  </p>

  <h2>Questions</h2>
  <p>
    Every tool on this site works exactly the same with or without cookies or analytics, because the tools don't
    depend on them. Questions? <a href="/contact/">Contact us</a>.
  </p>
</ContentPage>
